{
  "officeKey": "vespers",
  "label": "Vespers",
  "tradition": "BYZC",
  "description": "The Byzantine Evening Office (Hesperinos). Sections follow the standard order of Great Vespers in the Constantinopolitan rite.",
  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "opening",
      "label": "Opening",
      "notes": "The Usual Beginning precedes all Byzantine offices.",
      "items": [
        {
          "type": "rubric",
          "key": "usual-beginning-rubric",
          "text": "The Priest blesses: Blessed is our God, always, now and ever and unto ages of ages."
        },
        {
          "type": "sequence",
          "key": "usual-beginning",
          "items": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-1",
              "text": "Amen. Glory to Thee, our God, glory to Thee."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-2",
              "text": "O Heavenly King, O Comforter, the Spirit of Truth, Who art everywhere present and fillest all things, Treasury of blessings and Giver of life: come and abide in us, and cleanse us from every impurity, and save our souls, O Good One."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-3",
              "text": "Holy God, Holy Mighty, Holy Immortal, have mercy on us. (×3)"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-4",
              "text": "Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, both now and ever, and unto ages of ages. Amen."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-5",
              "text": "All-holy Trinity, have mercy on us. Lord, cleanse us from our sins. Master, pardon our iniquities. Holy One, visit and heal our infirmities for Thy Name's sake."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-6",
              "text": "Lord, have mercy. (×3)"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-7",
              "text": "Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, both now and ever, and unto ages of ages. Amen."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-8",
              "text": "Our Father, Who art in Heaven, hallowed be Thy Name. Thy Kingdom come, Thy will be done, on earth as it is in Heaven. Give us this day our daily bread; and forgive us our trespasses, as we forgive those who trespass against us; and lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-9",
              "text": "For Thine is the Kingdom, and the power, and the glory, of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit, now and ever, and unto ages of ages. Amen."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-10",
              "text": "Lord, have mercy.",
              "repeat": 2
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "key": "usual-beginning-11",
              "text": "Come, let us worship God our King.\nCome, let us worship and fall down before Christ our King and God.\nCome, let us worship and fall down before Christ Himself, our King and our God."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "psalmody",
      "label": "Introductory Psalmody",
      "notes": "Psalm 103 (LXX; = Psalm 104 Hebrew) is the fixed opening psalm of Vespers, chanted or read while the priest censes the altar.",
      "items": [
        {
          "type": "rubric",
          "key": "psalm-103-rubric",
          "text": "While the following psalm is read, the Priest performs the Evening Censing."
        },
        {
          "type": "psalm",
          "key": "psalm-103-lxx",
          "lxxNumber": 103,
          "hebrewNumber": 104,
          "label": "Psalm 103 (LXX) — Bless the Lord, O My Soul",
          "text": "Bless the Lord, O my soul. O Lord my God, Thou art very great. Thou art clothed with honor and majesty, Who coverest Thyself with light as with a garment, Who stretchest out the heavens like a curtain, Who layeth the beams of His chambers in the waters, Who maketh the clouds His chariot, Who walketh upon the wings of the wind, Who maketh His angels spirits, His ministers a flaming fire.\n\nHe laid the foundations of the earth, that it should not be removed forever. Thou coveredst it with the deep as with a garment; the waters stood above the mountains. At Thy rebuke they fled; at the voice of Thy thunder they hasted away. They go up by the mountains; they go down by the valleys unto the place which Thou hast founded for them. Thou hast set a bound that they may not pass over, that they turn not again to cover the earth.\n\nHe sendeth the springs into the valleys, which run among the hills. They give drink to every beast of the field; the wild asses quench their thirst. By them shall the fowls of the heaven have their habitation, which sing among the branches. He watereth the hills from His chambers; the earth is satisfied with the fruit of Thy works.\n\nHe causeth the grass to grow for the cattle, and herb for the service of man, that he may bring forth food out of the earth; and wine that maketh glad the heart of man, and oil to make his face to shine, and bread which strengtheneth man's heart.\n\nThe trees of the Lord are full of sap, the cedars of Lebanon which He hath planted, where the birds make their nests; as for the stork, the fir trees are her house. The high hills are a refuge for the wild goats, and the rocks for the conies.\n\nHe appointed the moon for seasons; the sun knoweth his going down. Thou makest darkness, and it is night, wherein all the beasts of the forest do creep forth. The young lions roar after their prey and seek their meat from God. The sun ariseth; they gather themselves together and lay them down in their dens. Man goeth forth unto his work and to his labor until the evening.\n\nO Lord, how manifold are Thy works! In wisdom hast Thou made them all; the earth is full of Thy riches. So is this great and wide sea, wherein are things creeping innumerable, both small and great beasts. There go the ships; there is that leviathan whom Thou hast made to play therein.\n\nThese all wait upon Thee, that Thou mayest give them their meat in due season. That Thou givest them they gather; Thou openest Thine hand, they are filled with good. Thou hidest Thy face, they are troubled; Thou takest away their breath, they die and return to their dust. Thou sendest forth Thy spirit, they are created, and Thou renewest the face of the earth.\n\nThe glory of the Lord shall endure forever; the Lord shall rejoice in His works. He looketh on the earth and it trembleth; He toucheth the hills and they smoke. I will sing unto the Lord as long as I live; I will sing praise to my God while I have my being. My meditation of Him shall be sweet; I will be glad in the Lord. Let the sinners be consumed out of the earth, and let the wicked be no more.\n\nBless thou the Lord, O my soul. The sun knoweth his going down. Thou makest darkness, and it is night. O Lord, how manifold are Thy works! In wisdom hast Thou made them all. Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, both now and ever, and unto ages of ages. Amen.\n\nAlleluia, Alleluia, Alleluia. Glory to Thee, O God. (×3)\n\nLord, have mercy. (×3)\n\nGlory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, both now and ever, and unto ages of ages. Amen."
        },
        {
          "type": "litany",
          "key": "great-litany",
          "label": "The Great Litany (Mirnaya Ektenia)",
          "text": "Deacon: In peace let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For the peace from above and for the salvation of our souls, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For the peace of the whole world, for the good estate of the holy churches of God, and for the union of all, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For this holy house and for those who enter it with faith, reverence, and the fear of God, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For our father and archbishop [Name], for our bishop [Name], for the honorable presbytery, the diaconate in Christ, for all the clergy and people, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For this country, its authorities and armed forces, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For this city (or: village, or: holy monastery), for every city and countryside and for the faithful who dwell therein, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For seasonable weather, for an abundance of the fruits of the earth, and for peaceful times, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For travelers by sea, by land, and by air; for the sick and the suffering; for captives and their salvation, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: For our deliverance from all affliction, wrath, danger, and necessity, let us pray to the Lord.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: Help us, save us, have mercy on us, and keep us, O God, by Thy grace.\nChoir: Lord, have mercy.\n\nDeacon: Commemorating our all-holy, immaculate, most-blessed and glorious Lady Theotokos and ever-virgin Mary, with all the saints, let us commend ourselves and each other and all our life unto Christ our God.\nChoir: To Thee, O Lord.\n\nPriest: For unto Thee is due all glory, honor, and worship: to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, now and ever, and unto ages of ages.\nChoir: Amen."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "lamp-lighting-psalms",
      "label": "Kathisma / Lamp-Lighting Psalms",
      "notes": "On weekdays a Kathisma from the Psalter is read. On Sundays and feasts, Psalm 140 (LXX) and companions are chanted as 'Lord, I Have Cried' with stichera.",
      "items": [
        {
          "type": "rubric",
          "key": "lord-i-have-cried-rubric",
          "text": "Lord, I have cried unto Thee, hear me. Hear me, O Lord. Lord, I have cried unto Thee, hear me; receive the voice of my prayer, when I cry unto Thee; hear me, O Lord."
        },
        {
          "type": "placeholder",
          "key": "stichera-at-lord-i-have-cried",
          "label": "Stichera at 'Lord, I Have Cried'",
          "status": "unresolved",
          "note": "Variable stichera appointed for this day or feast. Requires Octoechos tone, Menaion, or Triodion/Pentecostarion resolution. Not yet implemented."
        },
        {
          "type": "placeholder",
          "key": "kathisma-reading",
          "label": "Kathisma Reading",
          "status": "unresolved",
          "note": "Variable Psalter kathisma appointed for this day of the week. Requires Psalter cycle resolution. Not yet implemented."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "entrance",
      "label": "Evening Entrance and O Gladsome Light",
      "notes": "On Sundays and feasts the Evening Entrance is made with the Gospel. The ancient hymn Phos Hilaron (O Gladsome Light) is the fixed lamp-lighting hymn of Vespers.",
      "items": [
        {
          "type": "rubric",
          "key": "entrance-rubric",
          "text": "On Sundays and Great Feasts, the Evening Entrance is made here. Wisdom! Stand upright!"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "key": "o-gladsome-light",
          "label": "O Gladsome Light (Phos Hilaron)",
          "text": "O Gladsome Light of the holy glory of the Immortal Father, Heavenly, Holy, Blessed Jesus Christ! Now that we have come to the setting of the sun, and behold the light of evening, we praise God: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. For meet it is at all times to worship Thee with voices of praise, O Son of God and Giver of Life. Therefore all the world doth glorify Thee."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "prokeimenon",
      "label": "Prokeimenon",
      "notes": "A variable psalm verse chanted before the evening reading. Appointed by the day of the week or the feast.",
      "items": [
        {
          "type": "placeholder",
          "key": "daily-prokeimenon",
          "label": "Evening Prokeimenon",
          "status": "unresolved",
          "note": "Weekday prokeimenon resolved by HorologionEngine v1.2 from data/horologion/vespers-prokeimena.json. Table keyed by JS Date.getDay() (0=Sunday, 6=Saturday). Feast-rank overrides (Menaion / Triodion) are not yet implemented; the weekday default will display on all ordinary days."
        },
        {
          "type": "placeholder",
          "key": "vesperal-reading",
          "label": "Vesperal Reading (Paremiae)",
          "status": "unresolved",
          "note": "Paremiae (Old Testament readings) are appointed only on feasts of ranks 1–2 and during Great Lent. On all ordinary days this slot is resolved as omitted by HorologionEngine v1.2. Festal and Lenten reading resolution is deferred to v1.3+."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "aposticha",
      "label": "Aposticha",
      "notes": "Verses with stichera chanted at the close of the psalmody. Variable by day, tone, or feast.",
      "items": [
        {
          "type": "placeholder",
          "key": "aposticha",
          "label": "Aposticha Stichera",
          "status": "unresolved",
          "note": "Variable stichera with psalm verses, appointed by day of week or feast. Requires Octoechos or Menaion resolution. Not yet implemented."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "key": "nunc-dimittis",
          "label": "Song of Simeon (Nunc Dimittis)",
          "text": "Lord, now lettest Thou Thy servant depart in peace, according to Thy word; for mine eyes have seen Thy salvation, which Thou hast prepared before the face of all peoples: a light of revelation for the Gentiles, and the glory of Thy people Israel.\n\nHoly God, Holy Mighty, Holy Immortal, have mercy on us. (×3)\n\nGlory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, both now and ever, and unto ages of ages. Amen."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "dismissal",
      "label": "Dismissal",
      "notes": "The Troparion or Apolytikion of the day is sung before the dismissal. The Theotokion follows. The priest gives the dismissal blessing.",
      "items": [
        {
          "type": "placeholder",
          "key": "troparion-or-apolytikion",
          "label": "Troparion / Apolytikion of the Day",
          "status": "unresolved",
          "note": "Variable troparion appointed for the feast or the day. Requires Menaion or weekly cycle resolution. Not yet implemented."
        },
        {
          "type": "placeholder",
          "key": "theotokion-dismissal",
          "label": "Theotokion",
          "status": "unresolved",
          "note": "Variable Theotokion corresponding to the tone of the apolytikion. Not yet implemented."
        },
        {
          "type": "rubric",
          "key": "dismissal-rubric",
          "text": "Priest: Wisdom!\nChoir: Father, bless.\nPriest: He that is blessed, Christ our God, always, now and ever, and unto ages of ages.\nChoir: Amen. Preserve, O God, the holy Orthodox Faith and all Orthodox Christians, unto ages of ages.\nPriest: [Dismissal according to the feast or day]"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
